Kapsule Reasoning Agents — Specifications
Six specialized agents that compose the medication reasoning loop. Each entry lists purpose, tools/models it calls, and the exact EHR data slices it must pull.

1. Polypharmacy / Deprescribing Analyzer
Short description Detects unnecessary, duplicate, or harm-prone medications in the active regimen and produces a ranked, individualized deprescribing plan with taper schedules.
Tools needed
* Rules engine over Beers 2023, STOPP/START v3, Choosing Wisely
* Duplicate-therapy class matcher (drug-class ontology, e.g., RxNorm + ATC)
* Cascade detector (side-effect → downstream drug graph)
* LLM for taper-plan narrative + patient-specific rationale
* Fall-risk / anticholinergic burden calculators (ACB score)
EHR data required
* Active medication list (name, dose, route, frequency, start date, indication)
* Problem list and past medical history
* Age, sex, weight, frailty indicators, functional status
* Recent labs: BMP, CBC, LFTs
* Prior adverse drug events / intolerances
* Fall history, cognitive assessments (MMSE/MoCA if available)
* Goals of care / advance directives when present

2. GDMT Optimization Agent
Short description Compares the current regimen against current guideline-directed medical therapy for HFrEF, T2DM, CAD, CKD, and AFib. Flags missing therapies and quantifies expected mortality/morbidity benefit.
Tools needed
* Guideline knowledge base (ACC/AHA HF, ADA, KDIGO, ESC) with versioning
* Eligibility/contraindication checker
* Benefit estimator (NNT, ARR from landmark trials)
* LLM for evidence-grounded rationale + citation formatting
EHR data required
* Diagnoses with ICD-10 codes and onset dates
* Ejection fraction, NYHA class, most recent echo
* Labs: eGFR, potassium, HbA1c, LDL, BNP/NT-proBNP
* Vitals: BP, HR trends
* Active meds with doses (to detect sub-target dosing)
* Prior contraindications, allergies, intolerances
* Hospitalization history (HF admissions, MI)

3. Dose Intelligence Agent
Short description Validates every dose against renal, hepatic, age, and weight parameters. Flags contraindications and recommends adjusted doses before the order is signed.
Tools needed
* Renal + hepatic dose-adjustment tables (Lexicomp/Micromedex-style dataset)
* eGFR calculator (CKD-EPI 2021), Child-Pugh classifier
* Weight-based dosing calculator (pediatric or oncology if in scope)
* Trend analyzer over labs (not just latest value)
* Pre-order guardrail hook into CPOE
EHR data required
* Active + newly ordered meds with doses and frequencies
* Serial creatinine and eGFR (last 6–12 months)
* LFTs (AST, ALT, bilirubin, albumin, INR) for Child-Pugh
* Height, weight, BSA
* Age, sex
* Dialysis status and schedule
* Pregnancy status when relevant

4. Risk Monitoring Agent
Short description Continuously scores composite adverse-event risk (QT prolongation, bleeding, hyperkalemia, sedation, hypoglycemia, fall) across the regimen and generates a patient-specific monitoring plan.
Tools needed
* Composite risk calculators (HAS-BLED, CHA₂DS₂-VASc, QT-drug list, ACB)
* Time-series lab surveillance (delta detection, threshold triggers)
* Monitoring-plan generator (what lab, when, why)
* Alert deduplication + severity tiering
* LLM for plain-language rationale
EHR data required
* Active meds and recent starts/stops (change events matter)
* Labs trends: K+, Mg, creatinine, INR, glucose, TSH, CBC
* ECG data: most recent QTc, rhythm
* Vitals trends: BP, HR, SpO₂, weight
* Bleeding history, fall history, prior hypoglycemia
* Comorbidities driving risk (CKD, HF, cirrhosis)
* Encounter/admission history for outcome anchoring

5. Drug–Supplement Interaction Agent
Short description Reconciles prescribed meds with OTC drugs and supplements the patient reports, quantifies interaction severity, and produces mechanism-grounded recommendations.
Tools needed
* Interaction knowledge base covering supplements (NatMed, ODS, Lexicomp Natural Products)
* NLP parser for patient-reported supplements from notes / intake forms
* Severity grader (contraindicated / major / moderate / monitor) with mechanism + onset
* Bleeding / serotonergic / CYP-inhibition stack detectors
* LLM for patient-facing explanation
EHR data required
* Active med list
* Patient-reported OTC and supplement list (intake questionnaires, med rec notes, patient portal entries)
* Free-text clinical notes mentioning supplements ("takes turmeric daily")
* Labs affected by interactions: INR, LFTs, K+, glucose
* Transplant / anticoagulation / oncology status (high-consequence contexts)
* Allergies and prior adverse reactions

6. Cost Optimization Agent
Short description Finds therapeutically equivalent, formulary-preferred alternatives per the patient's plan, estimates copay impact, and ranks options by clinical equivalence, adherence risk, and out-of-pocket cost.
Tools needed
* Formulary + PBM tier data (per plan)
* Therapeutic-alternative mapper (same class, evidence-equivalent)
* Copay / cash-price estimator (GoodRx-style pricing feed, 340B when applicable)
* Prior-auth predictor
* Outcomes model (quality + safety + cost delta per switch)
* LLM for member-facing explanation
EHR data required
* Active meds with NDC/RxNorm codes
* Insurance plan + PBM identifier
* Refill history and adherence signals (PDC, gap days) from pharmacy claims
* Patient-reported cost barriers ("stopped due to cost" notes)
* Diagnoses (to confirm indication for alternative)
* Prior-auth history and denials
* Allergies and intolerances (to filter alternatives)

Cross-cutting notes
* Shared FHIR resources every agent reads: Patient, MedicationRequest, MedicationStatement, AllergyIntolerance, Condition, Observation (labs + vitals), Encounter.
* Shared writes: each agent emits a normalized Recommendation with tier, specialty, confidence, orderTarget, and evidence[] — matching the existing Recommendation type in src/lib/patients.ts.
* Orchestration: a router agent dispatches patient events (new lab, new order, admit/discharge) to the relevant subset instead of running all six on every change.
